                <section class="exc-content">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="exc-container">
                                                                                                        <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How To Do</h2>
                                    <ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Find a dual cable machine with both pulleys open for use.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Adjust the cable setting to about the height of your head. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Latch on the handle attachments to each cable pulley. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Position yourself directly in front and the middle of both cable pulleys with feet shoulder-width apart. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Grab the handles in the opposite hand (e.g., the left pulley handle is gripped with the right hand). </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Both arms should be extended and crossed over each other. If need be, take a step back to create enough space to extend the arms out for the exercise’s movement. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Keep a neutral grip with palms facing each other. Maintain a slight bend in the elbows.  </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Squeeze your shoulder blades together and keep the back straight. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Decide which arm you want on top or under the other for the crossover movement. Another option is to alternate for each repetition.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Draw the cables across your body to the other side and as far back as possible. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Slowly return to the starting position. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Repeat for the desired number of repetitions and sets.</span></li></ol>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Tips From Expert</h2>
                                    <ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Think of extending your arms out to the side like you’re about to give someone a big bear hug. Use this visual cue to extend the arms to the sides for crossover movement. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do not flex your wrists during the movement. All the movement should primarily be happening at the shoulder joint to better engage the upper body muscles. Avoid placing unnecessary strain on the wrist joints. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Prioritize maintaining a slight bend in the elbow throughout the movement. This reduces strain on the shoulder and wrist joints and better engages the targeted muscles. </span></li></ul>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Optimal Sets and Reps</h2>
                                    <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The ideal sets and reps can vary depending on your personal fitness goals. For example, a bodybuilder typically focuses on hypertrophy over endurance training, performing more sets and fewer reps.</span></p>                                                                                <div style="overflow: auto">
                                                <figure class="wp-block-table">
                                                    <table>
                                                        <thead>
                                                            <tr>
                                                                <th>Training Type</th>
                                                                <th>Sets</th>
                                                                                                                                    <th>Reps</th>
                                                                                                                            </tr>
                                                        </thead>
                                                        <tbody>
                                                                                                                            <tr>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                        <td>Strength Training</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>2–5</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>3–5</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        </tr>
                                                                                                                            <tr>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                        <td>Hypertrophy</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>3–4</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>6–12</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        </tr>
                                                                                                                            <tr>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                        <td>Endurance Training</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>2–3</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>10–15</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        </tr>
                                                                                                                            <tr>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                        <td>Power Training</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>1–3</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>2–5</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        </tr>
                                                                                                                    </tbody>
                                                    </table>
                                                    <figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets & Reps of Standing Cable Rear Delt Fly                                                    </figcaption>
                                                </figure>
                                            </div>
                                                                        </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How to Put in Your Workout Split</h2>
                                    <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The standing cable rear delt fly is an upper-body exercise that </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7706677/#:~:text=Regarding%20the%20posterior%20portion%20of%20the%20deltoid%2C%20Botton%20et%20al.%20(2013)%20and%20Franke%20et%20al.%20(2015)%20reported%20higher%20muscle%20activation%20of%20this%20muscle%20portion%20by%20the%20reverse%20pec%20deck%20fly%20exercise%20than%20a%20seated%20row%20or%20inclined%20pulldown." target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">targets the posterior deltoids</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. The upper trapezius muscle is also active du</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">ring this m</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">ovement. The exercise utilizes a dual cable pulley machine to perform the crossover motion and place tension on the rear delt muscles. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This exercise should be incorporated into upper body days or alongside other </span><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/cable-shoulder-workouts" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">cable shoulder workouts</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for upper and lower body splits. Regarding muscle-focused splits, like back and biceps, the standing cable rear delt fly would be best suited for shoulder or arm days. For push and pull split programs, this exercise would be best suited for pull days.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Determining your fitness goals is advantageous for lifters as this can emphasize your training focus, such as hypertrophy or endurance. When adding this exercise to your workout split, ensure you perform the correct sets and repetitions for your goals. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This movement is a </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5744434/#:~:text=In%20conclusion%2C%20the,SJ%20exercises%20alone." target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">compound exercise</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> incorporating multiple joints and muscle groups. Ideally, it should be performed near the beginning rather than the end of the workout, as it requires more energy. Begin with a lower weight to prioritize form, before increasing intensity with heavier loads. </span></p>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        </div>
            </div>
